04364nam a22005175i 9780773548879DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172017xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735488797 a10.1515/97807735488792doi  a(DE-B1597)655104  a(OCoLC)958271829  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBP128.17 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a297.1227211 aReda, Nevin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe al-Baqara Crescendo :bUnderstanding the Qur'an's Style, Narrative Structure, and Running Themes /cNevin Reda. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource :b14 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAdvancing Studies in Religion ;v100tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tHow to Read the Qur’an Holistically: Understanding the Rationale -- tBeginning at the Beginning: Al-Fātiḥa as a Prelude to Surat al-Baqara -- tSymmetry and a Mounting Dynamic: Al-Baqara’s Skeletal Outline -- tThematic Affirmation: Al-Baqara’s Chiastic Structure -- t“God as Guide”: Surat al-Baqara’s Running Theme in the Divine Self-Revelatory Reading -- tPlacing Humanity at the Focal Point: “Responsibility” as the Pedagogical Running Theme of Surat al-Baqara -- tWindows into the Tradition: Al-Biqā‘ī and al-Ṭabāṭabā’ī on Surat al-Baqara -- tConclusion -- tAppendix -- tGlossary -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRecent manuscript evidence from al-Jami` al-Kabir in ?an ‘a’ suggests that the Qur’an took its final shape well before 671 CE. Irrespective, however, of who composed it or when it was compiled, questions remain about whether the Qur’an followed any kind of preconceived plan or compositional schema that makes sense in today’s world. In The al-Baqara Crescendo, Nevin Reda introduces a bold new avenue of research: the poetics of Qur'anic narrative structure. Focusing on Surat al-Baqara, the longest and most challenging of the suras, she explores the beauty and rationale behind the Qur'an’s unusual organization. Reda argues that the sura – often dismissed by Muslim traditionalists and Orientalist critics as a baffling collection of disjointed material – can be appreciated as a coherent composition if it is approached as a spoken text. Calling attention to oral organizational techniques such as repetition, this book’s repertoire of figures showcases Surat al-Baqara’s ingenious layout and pinpoints the sophisticated meanings that are embedded within it. Incorporating insights from literary theory and Biblical studies, the author advances inclusivity and intercultural bridge-building in the study of scripture. In an engaging narrative that is bound to captivate and challenge the reader, Reda communicates a deep love and thorough command of her subject, all while presenting a significant new development in Islamic feminist hermeneutics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017z978311127619940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077354887940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773548879423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773548879/original  a978-3-11-127365-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-127619-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles